I have an autistic interest in alternate history, and long ago I began creating a setting for a story that would be set in, I thought, the worst possible world where there was still some hope things could be better.

Backstory: some factions in the USSR took control as the country was breaking up long enough to attempt that invasion of western Europe that NATO was formed to deter, and some nukes got thrown around, enough to increase the background count enough that childhood cancers have become one of the most common causes of death in developed countries in the Northern Hemisphere. The US is bankrupt and at the low-intensity conflict stage of a civil war, sliding ever faster toward collapse. Interdimensional contact was made with a low-tech civilization where magic worked, and one of the local royals, against the advice of the security consultant she hired--a hardcase veteran of the war whose unit got nuked by the Russians at Wurzburg, and who is the only one of his unit that survived the war that hasn't already died of leukemia--attempted a charity/goodwill tour of North America and promptly got blinded and maimed when her motorcade passed a very sophisticated EFP type roadside bomb planted by one of a dozen factions of batshit insane fanatics who have already started killing each other and the government hasn't even finished falling yet. The security consultant she'd hired, who had fallen in love with her--but never spoke a word about it to anyone, no last-minute anguished confession--sacrificed himself so that her people could take her back through the portal and close it off permanently. The end.

I would argue against this as a realistic option
In fact, it would be in the best interests of politicians to keep the anthros in the general population. By concentrating them, you do one of two things
1: give them a guaranteed voice in the government, which means they likely would split off and take land with them
2: or, you end up with a "reservation" system where they're a financial burden, not to mention a breeding ground for crime

But as modern politics goes, these would fail
My next point is that the anthros (and since we're using wolves in this case) would become highly balkanized and/or fragmented.
So a small group might try, but the odds are against them.

The most realistic possibility is the most frightening for us: the world's governments decide to genocide these TF'ed freaks before their illness spreads. A very few escape, and some centuries later there's a few self-sufficient homesteads out in the most inaccessible spots.
